  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Mark 9:20-22",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Mark 9:20-22",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And when he saw him ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— When the child saw Jesus, being brought to him by his father: when his deliverance was at hand; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "immediately the spirit tore him ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Made his last, grand effort to destroy him. Is it not generally so, before Satan relinquishes his power over a soul of which he has long had possession? ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And he ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(Christ) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "asked, How long is it, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — The Lord Jesus made this inquiry for the same reason for which he suffered Satan to make the violent attack upon the youth just mentioned, namely, that the spectators might be impressed with a more lively sense of his deplorable condition. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And he said, From a child ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Greek, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "παιδιοθεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "from his childhood, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or, as some render it, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "from his infancy. And ofttimes it ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— The evil spirit; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "hath cast him into the fire, &c., to destroy him ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Such is the power it has over him, and such its infernal rage and malice! ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "But if thou canst do any thing ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— In so desperate a case; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "have compassion on us ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— On me as well as him; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and help us ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— The afflicted father, greatly discouraged by the inability of our Lord’s disciples, and dispirited by the sight of his son’s misery, and by the remembrance of its long continuance, was afraid this possession might surpass the power of Jesus himself, and therefore spoke thus, expressing his doubts and fears in a manner very natural, and yet strongly pathetic, and obliquely interesting the honour of Christ in the issue of the affair.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "9:14-29 The father of the suffering youth reflected on the want of power in the disciples; but Christ will have him reckon the disappointment to the want of faith. Very much is promised to our believing. If thou canst believe, it is possible that thy hard heart may be softened, thy spiritual diseases may be cured; and, weak as thou art, thou mayest be able to hold out to the end. Those that complain of unbelief, must look up to Christ for grace to help them against it, and his grace will be sufficient for them. Whom Christ cures, he cures effectually. But Satan is unwilling to be driven from those that have been long his slaves, and, when he cannot deceive or destroy the sinner, he will cause him all the terror that he can. The disciples must not think to do their work always with the same ease; some services call for more than ordinary pains.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And wheresoever - In whatever place - at home or abroad, alone or in public.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He teareth him - He rends, distracts, or throws him into convulsions.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He foameth - At the mouth, like a mad animal. Among us these would all be considered as marks of violent derangement or madness.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And pineth away - Becomes thin, haggard, and emaciated. This was the effect of the violence of his struggles, and perhaps of the want of food.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "And pineth away - Becomes thin, haggard, and emaciated. This was the effect of the violence of his struggles, and perhaps of the want of food.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
